    <!-- WHAT ORGANIC MEANS -->
    <h2>What USDA Organic Means for Gummy Bears</h2>

    <p>The USDA Organic seal on gummy bears is not marketing — it is a legally enforced standard with annual third-party auditing. Here is what it guarantees and what it does not.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>What Organic Guarantees</h3>
        <p>95%+ organic ingredients, no synthetic pesticides, no synthetic fertilizers, no GMOs, no artificial colors, no artificial flavors, no artificial preservatives. Manufacturing must follow organic handling protocols.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="eye" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>What Organic Does NOT Guarantee</h3>
        <p>Organic does not mean vegan (organic gelatin exists), low-sugar (organic cane sugar is still sugar), allergen-free, or non-GMO (though organic prohibits GMOs by default). It addresses farming practices, not nutritional profile.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Natural Colorants</h3>
        <p>Organic gummy bears use colors from turmeric (yellow), carrot juice (orange), beetroot (red), purple sweet potato (purple), spirulina (blue/green), and annatto (gold). These replace synthetic Red 40, Yellow 5, and Blue 1.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="award" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Third-Party Verification</h3>
        <p>USDA Organic requires annual audits by accredited certifying agents. The certifier inspects ingredients, supply chains, and manufacturing facilities. Brands cannot self-certify — this is a regulated claim enforced by the USDA.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

