    <!-- SYNTHETIC DYES SECTION -->
    <h2>Why Parents Are Switching to Organic Gummy Bears</h2>

    <p>The single biggest driver of organic gummy bear sales is concern about synthetic food dyes. Here is what the research says and why it matters.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Red 40 (Allura Red)</h3>
        <p>The most commonly used food dye in the US. The European Food Safety Authority found sufficient evidence linking Red 40 to hyperactivity in children. EU products containing it must carry a warning label. No such requirement exists in the US.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Yellow 5 (Tartrazine)</h3>
        <p>Used in yellow and green gummy bears. Linked to hypersensitivity reactions in some children, particularly those with aspirin sensitivity. Banned in Norway and Austria. Requires warning labels in the EU.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>The Organic Alternative</h3>
        <p>Organic gummy bears use turmeric, carrot juice, beetroot, purple sweet potato, spirulina, and annatto for color. These are real foods with zero toxicity concerns. Colors may be less vivid, but they are completely safe.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>FDA Status</h3>
        <p>The FDA has reviewed synthetic food dyes multiple times and has not banned them in the US. However, some states (notably California) are moving toward restricting specific dyes in school foods. The easiest consumer solution is choosing USDA Organic, which prohibits all synthetic colorants.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- VERDICT -->
    <div class="verdict">
      <h3>The Verdict: Best Organic Gummy Bears in 2026</h3>
      <p><strong>YumEarth Organic Gummy Bears</strong> are our top pick because they deliver the best combination of USDA Organic certification, clean ingredients, great taste, and accessible pricing. At $1.29 per bag — with bulk options bringing the per-bag cost even lower — YumEarth eliminates the cost barrier that keeps many families from choosing organic. For the absolute cleanest ingredients, <strong>Surf Sweets</strong> leads with real fruit juice and top 14 allergen-free certification. For bulk buying, <strong>Black Forest Organic</strong> offers the best per-ounce pricing in the market.</p>
      <p>The organic gummy bear market gives parents a simple answer to the synthetic dye question: switch to USDA Organic and stop worrying about Red 40, Yellow 5, and Blue 1. The taste is comparable, the ingredients are transparent, and the price premium has shrunk to near-parity with mainstream candy brands.</p>
    </div>

